    "summary": "The Falklands War was a ten-week armed conflict between Argentina and the United Kingdom in 1982 over the Falkland Islands, South Georgia, and the South Sandwich Islands — British overseas territories in the South Atlantic that Argentina claimed as its own under the name Islas Malvinas. Argentina invaded the islands on 2 April 1982, and the British government under Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher dispatched a naval task force to recapture them.\n\nThe conflict lasted 74 days and resulted in British victory. Argentine forces surrendered on 14 June 1982. Approximately 649 Argentine and 255 British military personnel died, along with three Falkland islanders. The war demonstrated the continuing capacity of Britain to project military power across long distances and bolstered Thatcher's political standing significantly. In Argentina, the defeat contributed directly to the collapse of the military junta that had launched the invasion, hastening the transition to democracy.\n\nThe conflict raised significant questions about international law, sovereignty claims based on proximity versus population preference, and the operational lessons of modern naval warfare in an era of sophisticated anti-ship missiles.",
